qas.question: What is the Seattle newspaper as of 2010?
In what venue does the Seattle Post-Intelligencer publish?
In what year did the Seattle Post-Intelligencer  first publish?
What is the LGBT newspaper called?
Who sells the newspaper Real Change on the street?

context: As of 2010[update], Seattle has one major daily newspaper, <a0_0>The Seattle Times<a0_0/>. The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, known as the P-I, published a daily newspaper from <a2_0>1863<a2_0/> to March 17, 2009, before switching to a strictly <a1_0>on-line<a1_0/> publication. There is also the Seattle Daily Journal of Commerce, and the University of Washington publishes The Daily, a student-run publication, when school is in session. The most prominent weeklies are the Seattle Weekly and The Stranger; both consider themselves "alternative" papers. The weekly LGBT newspaper is the <a3_0>Seattle Gay News<a3_0/>. Real Change is a weekly street newspaper that is sold mainly by <a4_0>homeless persons<a4_0/> as an alternative to panhandling. There are also several ethnic newspapers, including the The Facts, Northwest Asian Weekly and the International Examiner, and numerous neighborhood newspapers.
